{{AfC comment|This https://www.japanese-wiki-corpus.org/history/Yamato%20no%20Kuni%20no%20Miyatsuko.html seems to be a translation of this. This is only english language source I could find on this https://www.jstor.org/stable/26864868 prognisis very bad for future development of this draft [[User:Immanuelle|'''Immanuel'''le]] ❤️💚💙 [[User_talk:Immanuelle|(talk to the cutest Wikipedian)]] 20:21, 17 March 2023 (UTC)}}{{Infobox Japanese clan}}

''''Yamato Kokuzo'''' was a [[Kuni no miyatsuko]] who ruled the central region of the later [[Yamato Province]]. Also spelled '''Oyamato kokuzo''' or '''Yamato no miyatsuko'''.

Their [[Ujigami]] is {{Ill|Yamato (god)|lt=Yamato|ja|倭大国魂神}}

__TOC__
{{Clear}}

== Overview ==

=== labels ===
In [[Kojiki|Kojiki]] and [[Nihon Shoki|Nihon Shoki]], he is referred to as '''Wajokokuzo''', and in ''[[Kujiki|Kokuzokuhonki]]''', '''Kunizokuhonki'''.

=== ancestor ===

* In the Kojiki, after [[Emperor Jimmu|Wakamoge-no-Mikoto]] left Takashima Palace in [[Kibi Province|Kibi Province]], he went to Hayasukumon {{Efn|thought to be the Toyo Straits, Akashi Straits, Kibi, etc.}}. and appointed '''Konezu-no-hiko''', a Kunitsugami deity who had guided him and made offerings to him, to the position of Yamakazo.
* In the Nihon-shoki (Chronicles of Japan), Shiinetsuhiko (Chinhiko), whom he met soon after leaving Hyuga, was appointed for the first time as the creator of Yamato in the 2nd year of Emperor Jinmu's reign, in recognition of his success in the Jinmu Eastern Expedition.
* The "Nihon-shoki" (Chronicles of Japan) "Kokuzo honki" tells that Shiinetsuhiko-no-mikoto, a grandson of [[Hoori|Hiko Hidemi no Mikoto]], who met and piloted the boat in Oyamakuni, was later appointed as the founder of Oyamakuni.
* In genealogical documents, Shiinetsuhiko is also called '''Uzubiko''', and in the "Yamato Shukune and Uminao" genealogy in the "Hyakke Genealogical Manuscripts" and the "Moro Genealogical Records", he is regarded as the grandson of Nurutama no Mikoto, the son of '''[[Watatsumi|Watatsumi Toyotamahiko-no-mikoto]]'''.

=== Clan ===
The name of the clan changed as the name of the country changed (Oyamatoji, Oyotokuji, Yamatoji, etc.). In [[Emperor Tenmu|Emperor Tenmu]]10 ([[681|681]]), Yamato Ryūmarō was given the [[Muraji|Ren]] surname, in [[12]] the family became Ren, in [[14]] the surname became Imazun, and in [[Nara period|Nara era]] Yamato Nagaoka and Mizumori were promoted to [[Sukune|Sukune]]. Their distant ancestor, Shiinetsuhiko, is said to be the great-grandson of [[Watatsumi|Watatsumi Toyotamahiko-no-mikoto]], and the family is classified as a Jigion by deity. He is also said to be of the same clan as the Yagi clan and the [[Azumi people|Azumi clan]]. Descendants include the Kubiki Kunizo, Aomi, Akashi Kunizo, and Kibi-Kaibe clans.

Note that the Wa are descended from [[Muryeong of Baekje|King Muryeong]], king of [[Baekje|Baekje]], so they are a separate lineage.

== base ==
Is it Cape Anaso-eup Oyachooka (former shrine site of Yamato Shrine)?

=== ruling domain ===
The area ruled by the Kunizo was then called '''Yamato Province''', later ''''[[Yamato Province|Yamato Province]]''', which is now [[Nara Prefecture]] [[Tenri, Nara|Tenri City]] and the surrounding area. (eastern part of the Nara Basin) was also ruled.

== Ujigami ==

* ''''[[Ōyamato Shrine|Yamato Za Okunitama Shrine]]''' (Ōyamato Shrine)
*: Or, Yamato Okunitama Shrine. In the 7th year of Emperor Sujin's reign ([[91 BC|91 BC]]), Princess Nu-no-shiroiru, who was the chief priestess of the shrine, lost her hair and became too thin to continue her rituals, and in a dream, she was told by the oracle [[Emperor]] that "If you make Iso-nagao City the host of a shrine to the deity Yamato Okunitama, the kingdom will be in peace. Suinin|Taruhito]] dynasty, Ichiso-Nagao City was founded as a shrine to the deity of the Great Goddess of the Sea of Japan.

=== Tomb ===

* ''''Nakayama Otsuka Tumulus'''
*: A front-recessed circular mound constructed in the early Kofun period, with Mikoto Sukune assumed to be its burial deity.
* '''Hatagozuka burial mound'''.
*: A forward-backward burial mound constructed in the early Kofun period, with Ichiso-Nagao City as the supposed interred object.
* '''Shimoikeyama Tumulus'''.
*: A forward-backward mound constructed in the early Kofun period, with Gojuno Sukune as the supposed interred person.

== Person ==

* '''Mimonosukune'''.
*: [[Kofun period|Kofun dynasty]] figure and national governor of the [[Emperor Sujin|Sungjin dynasty]]. Fifth grandson of Shiinetsuhiko.
* ''''Ichishino-Nagaoichi''''
*: A Kofun period figure and national governor of the [[Emperor Suinin|Taruhin dynasty]]. Son of [[Mikazukune]].
* ''''Isono Sukune''''.
*: A figure of the Kofun period, son of Ichiso-Nagaoichi.
* '''Kate-no-Sukune'''.
*: A figure of the Kofun period, son of Iguno Sukune.
* '''Naruko Sukune'''.
*: A personage of the Kofun period, son of Mukote Sukune.
* '''Yamato Agoko Kagome'''.
*: Kofun-era figure and national governor from the [[Emperor Nintoku|Nintoku dynasty]] to the [[Emperor Yūryaku|Yūryaku dynasty]]. Son of Naruko Shukune and brother of Somaro. He was almost killed by [[Emperor Richū|Renchū]] in a dispute over the succession to the throne, but he was saved by offering his sister Hinohime as an uname. Since then, it has become a custom for the Yamato clan to offer Une no Ehime to the Great King's family.
* ''''Somaro''''
*: A figure of the Kofun period and brother of Agokago. Also known as Maro Shukune, he was given the surname Oyamachinao.
* '''Nakuino-Atai'''.
*: A figure of the Kofun period, son of Soumaro.
* '''Yukiniwa no Atai''''.
*: A personage of the Kofun period, son of Namaikinao.
* '''Tehiko Atai'''.
*: Kofun period general and [[Emperor Kinmei|Kinmei Dynasty]] kokuzo. Son of Yukiniwa Nao, he was active in the [[Silla|Silla]] wars against [[Silla]].

== descendants ==

* Oyamato Gohyakusoku
*: There is a genealogical record that he was a son of Oyamato Ryumaro (Suzuki Shinnen, Hyakke Genealogical Manuscripts, vol. 21). Oyamakuninuzo, Ujigami, Gyobu Shosuke.
*: Yamato Nagaoka
*: [[Nara period|Nara era]] jurist. Son of Iotari (io-tari) of Oyamato. He was involved in the compilation of the [[Yōrō Code|Yōrō Ritsudō]]. His first name was Oyamato Imosun Kotohito. He later became Oyotoku Sukune, then Oyotoku Sukune, then Oyotoku Sukune again, and finally Yamato Sukune Nagaoka. He was also a Gyobu Shosuke, Minbu Daisuke and Kunmiya Daitada, Settsu Ryo, Mikawa Mamoru, Kawachi Mamoru, deputy chief of the Saikai Province patrol, and Sakyo Daio. Yamato-kunizo, Sho shikko-ranked. Compilation of the Reform Ritsuryo.
* Yamato Tateko.
*: A palm retainer of the Nimyo dynasty. He was given the surname of Asaomi. Later became a courtier and a fourth-ranked attendant.


