{{Interlanguage link|Yamato no Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|倭国造|simple}} was a [[Kuni no miyatsuko]] who ruled the central region of the later [[Yamato Province]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Yōko |first=ISSE |date=2019 |title=Revisiting Tsuda Sōkichi in Postwar Japan: "Misunderstandings" and the Historical Facts of the Kiki |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/26864868 |journal=Japan Review |issue=34 |pages=139–160 |jstor=26864868 |issn=0915-0986}}</ref>

Their [[Ujigami]] is {{Ill|Yamato Okunitama|lt=Yamato Okunitama|ja|倭大国魂神|simple}} of [[Ōyamato Shrine]]<ref>{{Cite web |title=International Symposium "Perspectives on Japanese history and literature from ancient historical records" |url=https://www.waseda.jp/inst/sgu/news-en/2019/04/12/5171 |access-date=2023-05-04 |website=Top Global University Project: Waseda Goes Global |language=en}}</ref>

{{ill|Agoko no Sukune|ja|倭吾子籠}} was of the clan and governor of Yamato Province<ref>{{Cite web |title=Episode 61: Bad Behavior and the People that Excuse It |url=https://sengokudaimyo.com/podcast/episode-61 |access-date=2023-05-04 |website=Sengoku Daimyo |date=April 2022 |language=en-US}}</ref>

During [[Jimmu's Eastern Expedition]] Saonetsuhiko was given the position by [[Emperor Jimmu]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Experts |first=Author : Japanese |title=Friday: Kojiki (「乞食」ではなく『古事記』ですヨ！！) #26 |url=https://japaneseexperts.net/972/ |access-date=2023-05-04 |website=Japanese Experts Net |language=en-US}}</ref> And Saonetsuhiko became their ancestor.<ref>https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/id=9159</ref>

