{{Short description|Japanese noble family}}
{{Infobox Japanese clan|province of origin=[[Yamato Province]]|home province=[[Yamato Province]]|image=Ohyamato-jinja Haiden.jpg|image caption=Oyamato Shrine, their main shrine|founder={{ill|Saonetsuhiko|ja|椎根津彦|qq=draft|qq=draft}},<br> {{ill|Ichishi no Nagaochi|ja|市磯長尾市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}}}

'''Yamato no Kuni no Miyatsuko''' was a title held by the clan{{Efn|Yamato no Atai clan}} who ruled the central region of the later [[Yamato Province]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Yōko |first=ISSE |date=2019 |title=Revisiting Tsuda Sōkichi in Postwar Japan: "Misunderstandings" and the Historical Facts of the Kiki |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/26864868 |journal=Japan Review |issue=34 |pages=139–160 |jstor=26864868 |issn=0915-0986}}</ref> Kuni no Miyatsuko were regional rulers subordinate to the [[Emperor of Japan]]. After the position was abolished they remained prominent as the priests of [[Ōyamato Shrine]]. Other kuni no miyatsuko this happened to include the [[Izumo clan]] of [[Izumo-taisha]], the [[Aso clan]] of [[Aso Shrine]], the [[Owari clan]] of [[Atsuta Shrine]], the {{ill|Munakata clan|ja|宗像氏|1=Munakata clan|fr|Clan Munakata|qq=draft|qq=draft}} of [[Munakata Taisha]],<ref>https://archive.today/20231025020641/https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/?id=8839</ref> and the [[Amabe clan]] of [[Kono Shrine]]<ref name="Bunka1">{{cite web |title=海部氏系図 |trans-title=Amebe shikeizu |url=https://kunishitei.bunka.go.jp/heritage/detail/201/777 |accessdate=August 20, 2020 |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |language=Japanese}}</ref>

Their [[Ujigami]] or clan god is [[Yamato Okunitama]] of [[Ōyamato Shrine]]<ref>{{Cite web |title=International Symposium "Perspectives on Japanese history and literature from ancient historical records" |url=https://www.waseda.jp/inst/sgu/news-en/2019/04/12/5171 |access-date=2023-05-04 |website=Top Global University Project: Waseda Goes Global |language=en}}</ref> Some scholars interpret the ''kami'' as being a variant or epithet of [[Ōmononushi]] who has much more widespread worship.<ref name="Ellwood-1990">{{Cite journal |last=Ellwood |first=Robert S. |date=1990 |title=The Sujin Religious Revolution |journal=Japanese Journal of Religious Studies |volume=17 |issue=2/3 |pages=199–217 |doi=10.18874/jjrs.17.2-3.1990.199-217 |jstor=30234018 |issn=0304-1042|doi-access=free }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Hardacre |first=Helen |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_Q81DQAAQBAJ |title=Shinto: A History |date=2017 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-062171-1 |language=en}}</ref>{{rp|22}} There is a complex myth about the origins of modern worship of [[Yamato Okunitama]] during the reign of [[Emperor Sujin]].<ref name="D-2012">{{Cite web |last=D |first=John |date=2012-11-10 |title=Teeuwen on Shinto |url=https://www.greenshinto.com/2012/11/10/teeuwen-on-shinto/ |access-date=2023-05-04 |website=Green Shinto |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name="japanpolicy">https://www.japanpolicyforum.jp/pdf/2016/no35/DJweb_35_cul_02.pdf</ref><ref name="freidok">https://freidok.uni-freiburg.de/fedora/objects/freidok:4635/datastreams/FILE1/content</ref><ref name="Nihongi">{{Citation |title=Book V |url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Nihongi:_Chronicles_of_Japan_from_the_Earliest_Times_to_A.D._697/Book_V |work=Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697, Volume 1 |access-date=2023-05-04}}</ref>

== History ==
[[File:Hibara-jinja, torii closeup.jpg|thumb|240x240px|[[Hibara Shrine]], at the foot of [[Mount Miwa]] in [[Sakurai, Nara]], identified as the place where the Yata-no-Kagami and the Kusanagi-no-Tsurugi were first enshrined after their removal from the imperial palace.]]
During [[Jimmu's Eastern Expedition]] {{ill|Saonetsuhiko|ja|椎根津彦|qq=draft|qq=draft}} was given the position of governor of [[Yamato Province]] by [[Emperor Jimmu]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Friday: Kojiki (「乞食」ではなく『古事記』ですヨ！！) #26 |url=https://japaneseexperts.net/972/ |access-date=2023-05-04 |website=Japanese Experts Net |language=en-US}}</ref> And Saonetsuhiko became their ancestor.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-10-26 |title=Saonetsuhiko {{!}} 國學院大學デジタルミュージアム |url=https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/id=9159 |access-date=2023-12-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231026183115/https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/id=9159 |archive-date=2023-10-26 }}</ref>

There is a complex myth about the reign of [[Emperor Sujin]] and its link to the worship of [[Yamato Okunitama]] and [[Amaterasu]]. There was a crisis during his reign and eventually the worship of [[Amaterasu]] and [[Yamato Okunitama]] were moved out of the imperial palace to separate shrines.<ref name="D-2012" /><ref name="japanpolicy" /><ref name="freidok" /><ref name="Nihongi" />

Worship of Amaterasu moved to [[Hibara Shrine]] and then many other shrines called {{ill|Moto-Ise Shrines|lt=|ja|元伊勢|1=Moto-Ise Shrines|qq=draft|qq=draft}} until eventually reaching [[Ise Jingu]].<ref name="Ellwood-1990"/>

By contrast the worship of [[Yamato Okunitama]] moved to [[Oyamato Shrine]], near [[Hibara Shrine]] and [[Omiwa Shrine]]. Yamato Okunitama was first entrusted to a daughter of [[Emperor Sujin]] named {{ill|Nunaki-iri-hime|ja|渟名城入姫命}}, but shortly afterwards, her health began to fail. It is recorded that she became emaciated and lost all of her hair, which rendered her unable to perform her duties.<ref name="aston150–164">{{cite book |author=Aston, William George. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_oEfAAAAYAAJ |title=Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697, Volume 2 |date=1896 |publisher=The Japan Society London |isbn=9780524053478 |pages=150–164 |author-link=William George Aston}}</ref> These efforts still did not alleviate the ongoing plague, so Sujin decreed that a [[divination]] be performed sometime during the 7th year of his reign, that would involve him making a trip to the plain of Kami-asaji, and invoking the [[Yaoyorozu no Kami|eighty myriad deities]].<ref name="aston150–164" />

After the divination, {{ill|Ichishi no Nagaochi|ja|市磯長尾市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a descendant of {{ill|Saonetsuhiko|ja|椎根津彦|qq=draft|qq=draft}} would conduct the rites pertaining to Okunitama, replacing the emaciated Nunaki-iri-hime.<ref name="Ellwood-1990"/> {{ill|Ichishi no Nagaochi|ja|市磯長尾市|qq=draft|qq=draft}} would be the ancestor of the Yamato no Kuni no Miyatsuko.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Page:Nihongi by Aston.djvu/208 |url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Page:Nihongi_by_Aston.djvu/208 |access-date=2023-10-24 |website=en.wikisource.org |language=en}}</ref>

{{ill|Yamato no Agoko|lt=Agoko no Sukune|ja|倭吾子籠|qq=draft|qq=draft}} was a notable member of the clan and governor of Yamato Province<ref>{{Cite web |title=Episode 61: Bad Behavior and the People that Excuse It |url=https://sengokudaimyo.com/podcast/episode-61 |access-date=2023-05-04 |website=Sengoku Daimyo |date=April 2022 |language=en-US}}</ref>

